Objects figures for 2021 show that all the 22 accidents involved grievous injuries to the people involved. Over the years, there has been a strong clamour to ensure safe cycling tracks on city roads, but due to lack of planning and space constraints, the demand has not been met yet. The scheme is already functional in Kochi around 200 ebicycles are likely to be introduced in the city for the project. Public bicycle sharing was initially a part of the smart city proposal, but concerns were raised regarding the feasibility of the project. heading: Road accident deaths up in Vizag this year

Over 1400 motorists were asked to campaign against drunken driving at important junctions for three days. The majority of the victims in road mishaps were two-wheeled riders, who were flouting traffic norms and engaging in accidents. heading: 74 of 185 accident victims in 2022 in Kolkata were pedestrians

The data also revealed that bikers had met with fatal accidents across the city for not abiding by traffic rules when they did not spot cops on the roads. "Though Kolkata has emerged as the best performer among other metro cities in terms of accident control, the total number of fatal accidents is still higher here than 26 other smaller cities these accidents mostly saw pedestrians’ deaths that is why all big projects of traffic police planned in 2023 like installation of boom barriers and ground led lights and development of model crossings and refuge islands in the middle of big crossings focus on the safety of pedestrians." said a senior officer of Kolkata police. heading: 182 killed in 461 accidents in Nashik city in 2022

Police officials said that an analysis of the data revealed that overspeeding was responsible for more than 70 of the fatalities. Additionally, 48 people died due to dangerous driving and 54 bikers had fatal accidents as they were not using helmets. Three others were killed due to wrongside driving and two died when they met with an accident while speaking on their cell phone. There are around 25 accident blackspots across the city. After the horrific accident at the Mirchi Hotel Chowk in October last year, the Nashik Municipal Corporation initiated steps to set up speed calming measures at these blackspots. Police Commissioner Ankush Shinde told TOI, "efforts will be made to bring down the number of s in the city. It is also necessary for people to follow the traffic rules and drive their vehicles cautiously for their own safety and the safety of others on the streets." There is also rising concern about the increasing number of vehicles on city roads every year, and thousands of new vehicles are added to city roads every year. In Friday's incident, the bike rider had taken a right turn around Parangiri Velu Park on Heber Road when he was fatally knocked down by the truck from behind while bad road and unsafe conditions for vehicles to take turns were blamed for the incident. The role of encroachments was undermined, Heber Road which connects Trichy District Court and Cantonment Police Station with congested Bhima Nagar and Palakkarai was once used for public transportation over the years as the road was encroached by shops, private and government buses were not allowed due to traffic bottlenecks. The recent eviction drives were not comprehensive enough to curtail shops from misusing public space. heading: 2 people killed in Road accidents in U’khand every day
sub-heading: An average of 2 people were killed every day on the roads of Uttarakhand in the period between 2013 and 2016, according to the Road accidents data compiled by the ministry of road transport and highways. The data was part of an answer given by minister of state for road transport and highways Mansukh L Mandaviya on December 28 in the Lok Sabha. In 2013, the state recorded 766 deaths in s, the number shot up to 878 in 2014 and to 913 in 2015. In 2016, a total of 962 people were killed in s in the Himalayan state, the data revealed. In all, a total of 3519 lives were snuffed out in s during the four-year period in Uttarakhand. The corresponding figure for other Himalayan states during this period was 4620 for Himachal Pradesh and 3857 deaths in Jammu & Kashmir.
